        ],
        [
          "Staff Generated History"
        ],
        [
          "You were a beautiful, bright young thing, coming into your own just as F. Scott Fitzgerald gave you an era. Born after the turn of the century, you came into your 20s just as America did and the music and the liquor and the intoxicating feeling of freedom and potential was what you lived for, was what you chased.  Was it a party? Was it a poetry reading? Was it a political rally?  You wanted it all and would sleep when you were dead.  But then suddenly, you found yourself standing face to face with death herself -- your Sire.  You'd had no idea she had lurked in so many shadows, watching and molding who you became in such a short amount of time.  'But I do not create, I only watch,' you said, as you bargined for your life.  'I know,' she whispered.  'I need someone to watch.'  So in Spring of 1927, Victoria Hathaway embraced you, eternally sealing your soul to hers, and to the night.  And so now, as you will till eternity -- you watch.  You watch as other Bright Young Things rise up and then flame out, and you write it all down. Sometimes you parlay it into a journal, sometimes into art house films, in the more modern nights you've tried 'blogging'.  All of it, as you have since meeting your lovely death bringing, you send to your Sire. If you don't, she will punish you, and you learned long ago that while the pain was exquisite, it was pain none the less. Your creation is appreciation of others."
        ],
